(85, 2, 'What is the proper form for a squat according to the database?', 'According to the database context, I found the following information for the proper form of a squat:\n\n- Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, toes pointing slightly outward.\n- Keep your back straight, chest up, and engage your core muscles.\n- Slowly lower your body down into a squat, keeping your weight in your heels.\n- Lower down until your thighs are parallel to the ground, or as low as you can comfortably go.\n- Push through your heels to return to standing, squeezing your glutes and quads at the top of the movement.\n- Keep your knees in line with your toes, and avoid letting them extend past your toes.\n- Avoid leaning forward or rounding your back.\n\nPlease note that proper form may vary slightly depending on individual needs and goals, but these general guidelines provide a solid foundation for a safe and effective squat.', '2026-04-25 07:28:52', '2026-04-25 07:28:52'),
(86, 2, 'Can you suggest a meal plan based on the database base on my bmi?', 'Based on your BMI of 27.04, which falls into the overweight category, I will suggest a meal plan that is tailored to your calorie needs. According to the database, a safe and effective calorie intake for weight loss for someone with a BMI of 27.04 is between 1800-2000 kcal per day.\n\nHere\'s a sample meal plan for you:\n\n**Breakfast**\n\n* Monday: Oatmeal with banana and almond milk (400 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 250g cooked oatmeal\n	+ 1 medium banana\n	+ 250ml almond milk\n* Tuesday: Scrambled eggs with spinach and whole wheat toast (350 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 2 large eggs\n	+ 1 cup fresh spinach\n	+ 2 slices whole wheat toast\n* Wednesday: Greek yogurt with berries and granola (300 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 200g Greek yogurt\n	+ 1 cup mixed berries\n	+ 2 tablespoons granola\n* Thursday: Avocado toast with poached eggs (400 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 2 slices whole wheat bread\n	+ 1 medium avocado\n	+ 2 large eggs\n* Friday: Smoothie bowl with banana, spinach, and almond milk (400 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 1 medium banana\n	+ 1 cup fresh spinach\n	+ 250ml almond milk\n	+ 1/4 cup sliced almonds\n* Saturday: Whole grain cereal with milk and sliced banana (300 kcal, 10g protein)\n	+ 250g whole grain cereal\n	+ 250ml milk\n	+ 1 medium banana\n* Sunday: Breakfast burrito with scrambled eggs, black beans, and avocado (400 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 2 large eggs\n	+ 1/2 cup cooked black beans\n	+ 1 medium avocado\n	+ 1 whole wheat tortilla\n\n**Lunch**\n\n* Monday: Grilled chicken breast with quinoa and steamed vegetables (400 kcal, 40g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled chicken breast\n	+ 100g cooked quinoa\n	+ 1 cup steamed vegetables\n* Tuesday: Turkey and avocado wrap (500 kcal, 30g protein)\n	+ 1 whole wheat tortilla\n	+ 2 slices deli turkey\n	+ 1 medium avocado\n	+ 1 cup mixed greens\n* Wednesday: Lentil soup with whole grain bread (400 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 250g cooked lentils\n	+ 2 slices whole grain bread\n	+ 1 cup mixed vegetables\n* Thursday: Grilled chicken breast with brown rice and steamed broccoli (400 kcal, 40g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled chicken breast\n	+ 100g cooked brown rice\n	+ 1 cup steamed broccoli\n* Friday: Tuna salad sandwich with mixed greens (400 kcal, 30g protein)\n	+ 120g canned tuna\n	+ 2 slices whole wheat bread\n	+ 1 cup mixed greens\n	+ 1 medium tomato\n* Saturday: Chicken Caesar salad (400 kcal, 30g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled chicken breast\n	+ 2 cups mixed greens\n	+ 1/4 cup Caesar dressing\n	+ 1 cup croutons\n* Sunday: Grilled chicken breast with roasted vegetables and quinoa (400 kcal, 40g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled chicken breast\n	+ 100g cooked quinoa\n	+ 1 cup roasted vegetables\n\n**Dinner**\n\n* Monday: Grilled salmon with roasted sweet potatoes and steamed green beans (400 kcal, 40g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled salmon\n	+ 100g roasted sweet potatoes\n	+ 1 cup steamed green beans\n* Tuesday: Chicken stir-fry with brown rice and mixed vegetables (400 kcal, 30g protein)\n	+ 120g cooked chicken breast\n	+ 100g cooked brown rice\n	+ 1 cup mixed vegetables\n* Wednesday: Beef and vegetable kebabs with quinoa (400 kcal, 30g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled beef\n	+ 100g cooked quinoa\n	+ 1 cup mixed vegetables\n* Thursday: Shrimp and vegetable stir-fry with brown rice (400 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 120g cooked shrimp\n	+ 100g cooked brown rice\n	+ 1 cup mixed vegetables\n* Friday: Grilled chicken breast with roasted asparagus and quinoa (400 kcal, 40g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled chicken breast\n	+ 100g cooked quinoa\n	+ 1 cup roasted asparagus\n* Saturday: Chicken and vegetable soup with whole grain bread (400 kcal, 20g protein)\n	+ 250g cooked chicken breast\n	+ 2 slices whole grain bread\n	+ 1 cup mixed vegetables\n* Sunday: Grilled chicken breast with roasted Brussels sprouts and sweet potatoes (400 kcal, 40g protein)\n	+ 120g grilled chicken breast\n	+ 100g roasted sweet potatoes\n	+ 1 cup roasted Brussels sprouts\n\n**Snacks**\n\n* Fresh fruit (100 kcal, 2g protein)\n* Raw almonds (150 kcal, 6g protein)\n* Greek yogurt with honey (150 kcal, 10g protein)\n* Hard-boiled egg (78 kcal, 6g protein)\n\nPlease note that this meal plan is a sample and may need to be adjusted based on your individual needs and preferences. It\'s also important to stay hydrated by drinking plenty of water throughout the day.', '2026-04-25 07:29:36', '2026-04-25 07:29:36'),
(87, 2, 'What should I do if I feel muscle pain after working out?', 'According to the database, muscle pain after working out is a common phenomenon known as delayed onset muscle soreness (DOMS). Here are some tips to help alleviate muscle pain after working out:\n\n1. **Stretching**: Gentle stretching can help reduce muscle tension and alleviate pain. Focus on static stretches that hold the muscle in a lengthened position for 15-30 seconds.\n2. **Foam Rolling**: Foam rolling can help reduce muscle tension and improve circulation. Use a foam roller to roll out the affected area, focusing on the muscle belly rather than the joints.\n3. **Warm or Cold Therapy**: Applying heat or cold to the affected area can help reduce pain and inflammation. Heat therapy, such as a warm bath or shower, can help relax muscles, while cold therapy, such as an ice pack or cold compress, can help reduce inflammation.\n4. **Rest and Recovery**: Adequate rest and recovery are essential for muscle repair and growth. Ensure you get 7-9 hours of sleep and take rest days as needed.\n5. **Massage**: Massage can help reduce muscle tension and promote blood flow. Consider self-massage techniques or seek the help of a professional massage therapist.\n6. **Over-the-Counter Pain Relievers**: Over-the-counter pain relievers, such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen, can help alleviate pain and reduce inflammation. However, always follow the recommended dosage and consult with a healthcare professional before taking any medication.\n7. **Proper Hydration**: Adequate hydration is essential for muscle function and recovery. Ensure you drink plenty of water throughout the day to help flush out toxins and promote muscle repair.\n8. **Electrolyte Balance**: Electrolytes, such as sodium, potassium, and magnesium, play a crucial role in muscle function and recovery. Consider consuming electrolyte-rich foods or supplements to help maintain a healthy balance.\n9. **Active Recovery**: Engage in low-intensity activities, such as yoga or light cardio, to promote blood flow and aid in muscle recovery.\n10. **Consult a Healthcare Professional**: If muscle pain persists or worsens, consult with a healthcare professional to rule out any underlying conditions that may be contributing to the pain.\n\nRemember, muscle pain after working out is a normal part of the exercise process. With proper recovery techniques and patience, you can alleviate muscle pain and continue to progress in your fitness journey.', '2026-04-25 07:31:14', '2026-04-25 07:31:14'),
(88, 2, 'Can you tell me the calories and protein for 100g of \'Eggplant, raw\'?', 'According to the database, the nutritional information for 100g of raw eggplant is:\n\n- Calories: 25 kcal\n- Protein: 0.7g', '2026-04-25 07:31:39', '2026-04-25 07:31:39'),
